Now, implementing the CSV parser. Let's think about how to split each line into fields.

For each line, iterate through each character, tracking whether we're inside a quoted field. When we encounter a comma, if not inside quotes, split. If inside quotes, continue. Also, handle escaped quotes (but the problem statement doesn't mention them, so maybe we can ignore them).

Let me write a function to parse a line into fields.

Function parseLine(line) {
  let fields = [];
  let inQuotes = false;
  let currentField = '';
  for (let i = 0; i < line.length; i++) {
    const char = line[i];
    if (char === '"') {
      inQuotes = !inQuotes;
      if (!inQuotes) {
        // End of quoted field
        fields.push(currentField);
        currentField = '';
      } else {
        // Start of quoted field
        currentField = '';
      }
    } else if (char === ',' && !inQuotes) {
      // Split on comma
      fields.push(currentField);
      currentField = '';
    } else if (char === ',' && inQuotes) {
      // Add comma to current field
      currentField += char;
    } else {
      // Add character to current field
      currentField += char;
    }
  }
  // Add the last field
  if (currentField) {
    fields.push(currentField);
  }
  return fields;
}

